e)</i> ‘bundle, parcel’ (Old French <i>troussel</i>), perhaps for a porter (see   Truss  ), or from the same word in the sense ‘stamp, mould (for stamping coins)’, for someone who minted coins.","variant of <b>Thrussell</b>, a nickname from Middle English <i>thros(t)el</i>, <i>thrus(t)el</i> ‘song thrush’ (Old English <i>thros(t)le</i>). Compare   Thrush  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Truss","meanings":["English (mainly Essex and Middlesex): metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>trusse</i> ‘bundle, package’ (Old French <i>trousse</i>), perhaps for a porter. See also   Trussell  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian <b>Trus</b>: nickname from <i>trus</i> ‘rabbit’, typically applied to someone thought to be a coward."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Trussell was born in 1175, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Osbert de Trussell, was 31 and his mother, Mrs Trussell, was 16. He had at least 1 son with Agnes FitzRobert of Loxley. He died in 1247, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1175–1247":"1175–1247","1177–1197":"1177–1197","1197–1265":"1197–1265","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","Abt 1162":"umbes 1162","1247":"1247","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1265":"1265","1177":"1177","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1160":"1160","about 1197":"umbes 1197","Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, England":"Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, England","Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Billesley, Warwick, England":"Billesley, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1175–1247":"1175–1247","1177–1197":"1177–1197","1197–1265":"1197–1265","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","Abt 1162":"noin 1162","1247":"1247","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1265":"1265","1177":"1177","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","about 1200":"noin 1200","1160":"1160","about 1197":"noin 1197","Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, England":"Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, England","Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marston Trussel, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Billesley, Warwick, England":"Billesley, Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1175–1247":"1175–1247","1177–1197":"1177–1197","1197–1265":"1197–1265","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1160–Female":"1160–Décédée